            <p style="color:black;font-family:calibri;text-align: justify; font-size:18px;">
                <b style="padding-left: 20px;">Introduction and background</b><div>
                    <div style="margin: 2px 21px; font-family:Georgia; font-size:16px; text-align: justify">
                        Liquidity has become an imposing issue for financial institutions around the world, and much more
                        so since bank regulations have become more onerous and comprehensive. The financial crisis and
                        its aftermath has brought liquidity into sharp focus, and under Banking regulations, Banks are
                        expected to calculate its regulatory capital based on the risks that they are exposed to and set aside
                        a minimum level of capital. They are also required to determine the level of High Quality Liquidity
                        Assets (“HQLA”) needed to fulfil liquidity requirements.<br /><br />
                        Collectively, these regulations are referred to as Basel 3 and the implementation of these rules are
                        known to be onerous, complex and costly. The liquidity rules are requirements that expects Banks to
                        maintain adequate liquidity to be able to meet its obligations. The two measurements of liquidity, as
                        specified in Basel 3, are the Liquidity Coverage Ratio (“LCR”) and the Net Stable Funding Ratio
                        (“NSFR”), with LCR focusing on the Bank’s short-term liquidity and NSFR on long term.<br /><br />
                        The combination of these two measures will require Banks to maintain sufficient levels of HQLA to
                        ensure compliance, and to optimise liquidity risks and positions. HQLAs are specific assets that are
                        unencumbered and are convertible quickly to cash (or cash itself) in times of stress. Therefore, it
                        becomes imperative that a bank maintain a level of HQLA that are neither too much or too little,
                        since too much will result in sub-optimal returns and too little will result in illiquidity, and ultimately,
                        insolvency.
                    </div>
                </div>
